"'''Skin Deep: The Fat Dancer's Tale'''" by [[A. C. Crispin]] provides the backstory of [[Askajian/Legends|Askajian]] dancer [[Yarna d'al' Gargan/Legends|Yarna d'al' Gargan]], and appeared in ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]'', which was published [[December]] [[1995]] by [[Bantam Spectra]].

==Plot summary==
On the night after the [[Battle of the Great Pit of Carkoon]]. [[Tessek/Legends|Tessek]] returns to [[Jabba's Palace/Legends|Jabba's Palace]] in a rush and reveals to the inhabitants of Jabba's [[Death/Legends|demise]], sending the palace into chaos. [[Yarna d'al' Gargan/Legends|Yarna d'al' Gargan]], an [[Askajian/Legends|Askajian]] dancer, is effectively freed from her servitude now that Jabba is dead and immediately takes this as an opportunity to flee to [[Mos Eisley/Legends|Mos Eisley]] and recover her children, whom Jabba is currently keeping as [[Prisoner/Legends|prisoners]] in the [[Desilijic Complex/Legends|Desilijic Complex]]. While recovering the necessary supplies to make the trip, Yarna meets [[Doallyn/Legends|Doallyn]], a [[Geranite/Legends|Geranite]] huntsman currently living in the palace due to business with Jabba. Needing a supply of cartridges of [[hydron-three|Hydron-3]] that Jabba also had stored in the complex in order to replenish his [[Breath mask|breathing mask]], Doallyn agreed to act as Yarna's [[Bodyguard/Legends|bodyguard]] in her journey.

The unlikely pair successfully navigate their way out of Jabba's Palace, with Doallyn saving Yarna from both an assault attempt by two of Jabba's guards, [[Tornik]] and [[Warlug]], and being attacked by [[Assassin/Legends|serial killer]] [[Dannik Jerriko]]. Using a [[Speeder/Legends|speeder]], they venture out into the [[Dune Sea/Legends|Dune Sea]]. While engaging in conversation, Yarna and Doallyn bond over their life stories.

As they near Mos Eisley, Yarna and Doallyn accidentally crash their speeder into a sand pit, right next to a [[Sleep/Legends|sleeping]] [[Krayt dragon/Legends|krayt dragon]]. The beast nearly kills Yarna, but Doallyn manages to slay it by firing a [[Blaster/Legends|blaster]] shot into its [[Sinuses|sinus cavity]]. Doallyn then extracts the [[Krayt dragon pearl/Legends|pearls]] from its [[Stomach/Legends|stomach]], but as he is cutting off a piece of the Krayt Dragon's tail as a trophy, he is knocked out when its tail twitches reflexively. By now, Doallyn has run out of Hydron-3 and is slowly dying. Yarna carries him to Mos Eisley, and uses some of the jewels she had been saving to free her children to instead buy him more Hydron-3, saving his life.

Doallyn is grateful to Yarna for her selfless act, but Yarna herself is morose, as she has lost her one chance at reclaiming her children. Fortunately, Doallyn repays her with the dragon pearls, which they use to buy back Yarna's children, as well as a [[Starship/Legends|spaceship]] to leave [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]]. After some debate, the pair decides to go to [[Geran/Legends|Doallyn's homeworld]].

==Continuity==
It was unclear as to whether [[Sergeant/Legends|Sergeant]] [[Doallyn/Legends|Doallyn]] was visible in the film [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']] ([[1983]]), as there were several helmeted warriors who matched his description. A black-helmeted spacer in a black jumpsuit was tossed down a set of stairs by [[Chewbacca/Legends|Chewbacca]] upon the [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiee's]] arrival at [[Jabba's Palace/Legends|Jabba's palace]]. Later, a gray-suited character wearing the same helmet was seen being cut down by [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] in the [[Bantha-II cargo skiff/Legends|skiff]] battle over the [[Sarlacc/Legends|Sarlacc]]. A digitally manipulated image of the gray-suited character was used to visually depict Doallyn in a [[1998]] expansion to the [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game]], but the black-suited version was the more accurate depiction. This black-suited, though, invited confusion with another similarly outfitted hunter named [[Bane Malar/Legends|Bane Malar]].<ref name="TERC" />

